<p>As the designer of the Musa Alphabet, of course I see Musa as the best solution.  Musa's biggest drawback is its unfamiliarity, but it's so easy to learn that this is quickly overcome.  But I'm also open to see what else we can come up with.

</p><p>When the IPA was invented, it was natural for the designers to base it on the Roman alphabet.  And if they had continued in accordance with some principles, it might have been a big success.  But the current version is just a jumble of symbols, with no system behind it.  Its great advantage should be its familiarity, but very few users of the Roman alphabet will find letters like <b>cxqɞʌɔɤʄɰɺɥʘʢ</b> familiar.  Meanwhile, modern acoustic analysis has made the IPA's articulatory model for vowels outdated, and the IPA relies too heavily on diacritics, which (in addition to being ugly) are often omitted.

